er Wars unfolds that historic struggle, offering glimpses into the political, social, and cultural life of the semi-rural, single-industry community. Hindered by economic depression, two World Wars, and Cold War intolerance, Local 480 faced fierce corporate, media, and religious opposition at home. Ron Verzuh draws upon archival and periodical sources, including the mainstream and labour press, secret police records, and oral histories, to explore the CIO’s complicated legacy in Trail as it battled a wide range of antagonists: a powerful employer, a company union, local conservative citizens, and Cooperative Commonwealth Federation (CCF) leadership. More than the history of a union, Smelter Wars is a cultural study of a community shaped by the dominance of a world-leading industrial juggernaut set on keeping the union drive at bay.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aIndustrial relationszBritish ColumbiazTrailxHistory. 0aIron and steel workersxLabor unionszBritish ColumbiazTrailxHistory. 0aLabor unionszBritish ColumbiazTrailxHistory. 0aSmeltingzBritish ColumbiazTrailxHistory. 0aSubsidieszBritish ColumbiazTrailxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh  aBritish Columbia.  aCCF.  aCanadian history.  aCold War.  aCongress of Industrial Organizations.  aTrail.  acommunism.  aethnicity.  alabor.  alabour.  amill.  amining.  arace.  asmelting.  aunion.  awartime.  awestern Canada.  awomen.  aworkplace.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754113240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487541132423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487541132/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Com